{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d6e50df3-fc8d-491b-98dd-e2decb770614","content":"Two things change with xUnit.net v3 + MTP:\n\n1. **`--filter` (VSTest syntax) → `--treenode-filter` (MTP syntax)** — MTP doesn't use the VSTest filter engine.\n2. **Operators change** — MTP uses glob paths and `[trait=value]` brackets instead of `Property~Value&Trait=Value`.\n\n**Translation:**\n\n| Old (VSTest) | New (MTP) |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` | `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` |\n| `Category=Smoke` | `[Category=Smoke]` |\n| `&` (AND) | combine into one expression |\n\n**Your new CI command:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*/**[Category=Smoke]\"\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args. The path `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` matches any test under a node containing \"IntegrationTests\", and `[Category=Smoke]` filters to tests with that trait.\n\nIf you run the test executable directly (since MTP produces a standalone exe):\n\n```bash\n./TestProject --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*/**[Category=Smoke]\"\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a533c130-4f45-49ad-842e-bc69c3bd47b7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3 with MTP (Microsoft Testing Platform). With MTP enabled (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner`), the test executable becomes a standalone executable and the filtering syntax changes.\n\nKey changes:\n1. With MTP, you run tests via `dotnet test` but the filter syntax changes from VSTest's `--filter` to MTP's `--filter` which has different syntax.\n2. The old VSTest filter: `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke`\n   - `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` means FQN contains \"IntegrationTests\"\n   - `Category=Smoke` means Trait \"Category\" equals \"Smoke\"\n   - `&` is AND\n\nWith MTP enabled, the filter syntax changes significantly—VSTest's property names and operators don't work the same way. MTP uses `--treenode-filter` for its native filtering approach, though there's a compatibility layer for `dotnet test` that attempts to translate the old syntax. I'm realizing that with xUnit v3 and MTP, the VSTest filter syntax doesn't apply—MTP uses its own filtering protocol entirely, so `--treenode-filter` with a path-based glob pattern is the way to go for structural filtering, while `--filter` would need to follow MTP's syntax instead. I'm clarifying how to pass the tree node filter when using `dotnet test` with MTP enabled—you can either append it after `--` or run the test executable directly with the filter argument, and the syntax remains the same for filtering by test name and category. The test tree structure is: Assembly > Namespace > Class > Method. The pattern `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` matches any node containing \"IntegrationTests\" and all its descendants, while `[Category=Smoke]` filters by the trait. I need to combine these correctly in MTP syntax—the property filter should attach to the path segment, so the proper syntax is `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**[Category=Smoke]`. Now I'm translating the old VSTest filter syntax to the new MTP format: `dotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"` becomes `dotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*/**[Category=Smoke]\"`.","outputTokens":1807,"requestId":"0C03:2B0E8:24725B:2ABB79:69F00620"},"id":"b8246555-307f-451b-bd62-9c5f9035f4b3","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:58:42.351Z","parentId":"21c9a8a4-945b-480b-8601-a448036a2b1e"}
